Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members to the US Federal Reserve's board gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future course.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to fail so badly in its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional self-examination is certainly warranted.
Yet while interest rate policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether it will use its immense power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, deny loans to fossil fuel companies, require banks to grant loans only to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer lending toward desired alternatives.
Furthermore, it could decide to explicitly pursue equality or ethnic justice through regulation by requiring banks to specify where and to whom loans are granted, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will take or should take, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a consequential decision: financial institutions could still largely obtain money for risky investments by selling short-term, interest-rate-sensitive debt securities, but armies of new regulators would now assess the riskiness of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of subprime mortgages in bank balance sheets.
Yet over the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually hit in early 2020, the Fed discarded its "Never again" promises from 2008 and intervened to an even greater extent.
In March, commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for ordinary U.S. Treasury securities.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The market corrections would have been easy, but obvious reforms were postponed.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially offering a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector rescue package - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, the "Powell put" - among other things - explicitly set a floor for corporate bond prices.
The predictable rebuttal to this criticism will be: So what?
Lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out any new fire with another flood of money.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives created by these strategies.
Why bother to make an effort and use cash reserves or balance sheet capacity to buy at falling prices, provide liquidity, or treat a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will inevitably outperform everyone and pocket the profits.
Why would a company issue stocks when it can simply take out a loan, knowing that the government will back the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why would investors hesitate to buy dubious securities when their value is guaranteed by another "Whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed during bad times?
No wonder that America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will bear the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, government bonds, and mortgages are piling up and waiting their turn to be rescued by Uncle Sam's bailout.
Yet each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into bailouts, and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up to a major disaster – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least recognized the moral hazard and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, people indulged only in self-satisfaction regarding the bailouts.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as it failed to foresee the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests regarding "climate risks," will certainly overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next sovereign bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask the question about these mentioned events.
And although jargon about "networks," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define "systemic" risk beyond it becoming a catch-all term that grants regulators sweeping powers.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to predict risks, accurately measure the value of financial institutions' assets, or ensure that massive debts can always be paid off.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands behind mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it claims that large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit few Americans.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations presents a major barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is meaningless.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires no prophetic skills from regulators.
The Fed scandalously blocked companies in the narrow banking and payment services sector that could help meet the financial needs of many people in America.
Before committing to the salvation of the planet and rectifying injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it has fulfilled its fundamental duty of protecting the financial system.
